	<li class="comment byuser comment-author-otto bypostauthor odd alt depth-2 parent" id="comment-12223" itemprop="comment" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Comment">
		<div id="div-comment-12223" class="comment-body">
		<div class="comment-author" itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
	<img alt='' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/0994d5e2e158a24ba8017c2525d78263?s=48&amp;d=retro&amp;r=X' class='avatar avatar-48 photo' height='48' width='48' />	<cite itemprop="name"><a itemprop='url' href='http://ottodestruct.com' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>Otto</a></cite> <span class="says">says:</span>	</div>

	<div class="comment-meta commentmetadata"><a itemprop="url" href="http://ottopress.com/2010/wordpress-3-0-multisite-domain-mapping-tutorial/comment-page-12/#comment-12223">
		<time itemprop="dateCreated" datetime="2014-01-08T19:25:41+00:00">January 8, 2014 at 7:25 pm</time></a>	</div>

	<div itemprop="text"><p>I don&#8217;t know much about Cloudflare&#8217;s DNS system, but probably. The trick isn&#8217;t configuring DNS, usually, the trick is configuring your webserver properly.</p>
<p>Several things have to happen to do domain mapping like this:<br />
- The DNS has to be configured to point the domain at the IP of your host.<br />
- The host web server has to be configured to have those domains mapped to the WordPress installation.</p>
<p>This plugin then takes over after that, and maps the domain to the individual blog in your multisite installation.</p>
</div>

	<div class="reply">
	<a class='comment-reply-link' href='/2010/wordpress-3-0-multisite-domain-mapping-tutorial/?replytocom=12223#respond' onclick='return addComment.moveForm("div-comment-12223", "12223", "respond", "166")'>Reply to this comment</a>	</div>
